{"id":"1010.5437","submitter":"Carlo Rovelli","authors":"Carlo Rovelli, Matteo Smerlak","title":"In quantum gravity, summing is refining","comments":"Substantially revised version. Corrects a mistake pointed out by\n  Jurek Lewandowski in the first version. 5 pages. Title has changed","journal-ref":"Class. Quantum Grav. 29 (2012) 055004","doi":"10.1088/0264-9381/29/5/055004","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In perturbative QED, the approximation is improved by summing more Feynman\ngraphs; in non-perturbative QCD, by refining the lattice. Here we observe that\nin quantum gravity the two procedures may well be the same. We outline the\ncombinatorial structure of spinfoam quantum gravity, define the continuum\nlimit, and show that under general conditions refining foams is the same as\nsumming over them. The conditions bear on the cylindrical consistency of the\nspinfoam amplitudes and on the presence of appropriate combinatorial factors,\nrelated to the implementation of diffeomorphisms invariance. Intuitively, the\nsites of the lattice are points of space: these are themselves quanta of the\ngravitational field, and thus a lattice discretization is also a Feynman\nhistory of quanta.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 26 Oct 2010 15:47:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 27 Oct 2010 12:03:19 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 3 May 2011 14:37:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-20"}
